  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (such as proceeds from criminal activities) appear to be legitimate by disguising its true source. This activity undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates criminal enterprises, and disrupts economic stability.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2007 and has been updated to strengthen regulations. The law requires financial institutions and certain non-financial entities to implement measures to prevent, detect, and report suspicious transactions related to money laundering. Violations of anti-money laundering laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and criminal prosecution.\n\nChina, as a responsible member of the international community, actively participates in global efforts to combat money laundering, working with organizations such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** to uphold international standards in this area.",
